[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The core of Apache Hadoop consists of a storage part, known as Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS), and a processing part which is a MapReduce programming model.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Hadoop splits files into large blocks and distributes them across nodes in a cluster.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] It then transfers packaged code into nodes to process the data in parallel.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] This approach takes advantage of data locality, where nodes manipulate the data they have access to.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] This allows the dataset to be processed faster and more efficiently than it would be in a more conventional supercomputer architecture that relies on a parallel file system where computation and data are distributed via high-speed networking.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Apache Hadoop's MapReduce and HDFS components were inspired by Google papers on MapReduce and Google File System.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop framework itself is mostly written in the Java programming language, with some native code in C and command line utilities written as shell scripts.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Perl language can be easily used with Hadoop Streaming to implement the map and reduce parts of the user's program.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] According to its co-founders, Doug Cutting and Mike Cafarella, the idea of Hadoop was conceived in the Google File System paper that was published in October 2003.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The concept was extended in the Google paper *"MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters".* Development started on the Apache Nutch project, but was moved to the new Hadoop subproject in January 2006.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Doug Cutting, who was working at Yahoo! at the time, named it after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The initial code that was factored out of Nutch consisted of about 5,000 lines of code for HDFS and about 6,000 lines of code for MapReduce.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] In March 2006, Owen O'Malley was the first committer to add to the Hadoop project; Hadoop 0.1.0 was released in April 2006.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] It continues to evolve through contributions that are being made to the project.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The first design document for the Hadoop Distributed File System was written by Dhruba Borthakur in 2007.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Hadoop consists of the *Hadoop Common* package, which provides file system and operating system level abstractions, a MapReduce engine (either MapReduce/MR1 or YARN/MR2) and the Hadoop Distributed File System (HDFS).
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The Hadoop Common package contains the Java Archive (JAR) files and scripts needed to start Hadoop.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] For effective scheduling of work, every Hadoop-compatible file system should provide location awareness, which is the name of the rack, specifically the network switch where a worker node is.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Hadoop applications can use this information to execute code on the node where the data is, and, failing that, on the same rack/switch to reduce backbone traffic.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] HDFS uses this method when replicating data for data redundancy across multiple racks.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] This approach reduces the impact of a rack power outage or switch failure; if any of these hardware failures occurs, the data will remain available.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] A small Hadoop cluster includes a single master and multiple worker nodes.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The master node consists of a Job Tracker, Task Tracker, NameNode, and DataNode.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] A slave or *worker node* acts as both a DataNode and TaskTracker, though it is possible to have data-only and compute-only worker nodes.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] These are normally used only in nonstandard applications.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Hadoop requires the Java Runtime Environment (JRE) 1.6 or higher.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The standard startup and shutdown scripts require that Secure Shell (SSH) be set up between nodes in the cluster.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] In a larger cluster, HDFS nodes are managed through a dedicated NameNode server to host the file system index, and a secondary NameNode that can generate snapshots of the namenode's memory structures, thereby preventing file-system corruption and loss of data.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Similarly, a standalone JobTracker server can manage job scheduling across nodes.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop MapReduce is used with an alternate file system, the NameNode, secondary NameNode, and DataNode architecture of HDFS are replaced by the file-system-specific equivalents.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The *Hadoop distributed file system* (HDFS) is a distributed, scalable, and portable file system written in Java for the Hadoop framework.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] A Hadoop instance is divided into HDFS and MapReduce.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] HDFS is used for storing the data and MapReduce is used for processing data.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Top three are Master Services/Daemons/Nodes and bottom two are Slave Services.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Master Services can communicate with each other and in the same way Slave services can communicate with each other.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Name Node is a master node and Data node is its corresponding Slave node and can talk with each other.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Hadoop cluster has nominally a single namenode plus a cluster of datanodes, although redundancy options are available for the namenode due to its criticality.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Each datanode serves up blocks of data over the network using a block protocol specific to HDFS.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The file system uses TCP/IP sockets for communication.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Clients use remote procedure calls (RPC) to communicate with each other.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] HDFS stores large files (typically in the range of gigabytes to terabytes) across multiple machines.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] It achieves reliability by replicating the data across multiple hosts, and hence theoretically does not require redundant array of independent disks (RAID) storage on hosts (but to increase input-output (I/O) performance some RAID configurations are still useful).
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] With the default replication value, 3, data is stored on three nodes: two on the same rack, and one on a different rack.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Data nodes can talk to each other to rebalance data, to move copies around, and to keep the replication of data high.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] HDFS is not fully POSIX-compliant, because the requirements for a POSIX file-system differ from the target goals of a Hadoop application.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The trade-off of not having a fully POSIX-compliant file-system is increased performance for data throughput and support for non-POSIX operations such as Append.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] In May 2012, high-availability capabilities were added to HDFS, letting the main metadata server called the NameNode manually fail-over onto a backup.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The project has also started developing automatic fail-overs.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The HDFS file system includes a so-called *secondary namenode*, a misleading term that some might incorrectly interpret as a backup namenode when the primary namenode goes offline.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] In fact, the secondary namenode regularly connects with the primary namenode and builds snapshots of the primary namenode's directory information, which the system then saves to local or remote directories.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] These checkpointed images can be used to restart a failed primary namenode without having to replay the entire journal of file-system actions, then to edit the log to create an up-to-date directory structure.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Because the namenode is the single point for storage and management of metadata, it can become a bottleneck for supporting a huge number of files, especially a large number of small files.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] HDFS Federation, a new addition, aims to tackle this problem to a certain extent by allowing multiple namespaces served by separate namenodes.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Moreover, there are some issues in HDFS such as small file issues, scalability problems, Single Point of Failure (SPoF), and bottlenecks in huge metadata requests.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] One advantage of using HDFS is data awareness between the job tracker and task tracker.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The job tracker schedules map or reduce jobs to task trackers with an awareness of the data location.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] For example: if node A contains data (a, b, c) and node X contains data (x, y, z), the job tracker schedules node A to perform map or reduce tasks on (a, b, c) and node X would be scheduled to perform map or reduce tasks on (x, y, z).
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] This reduces the amount of traffic that goes over the network and prevents unnecessary data transfer.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] When Hadoop is used with other file systems, this advantage is not always available.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] This can have a significant impact on job-completion times as demonstrated with data-intensive jobs.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] HDFS was designed for mostly immutable files and may not be suitable for systems requiring concurrent write operations.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] HDFS can be mounted directly with a Filesystem in Userspace (FUSE) virtual file system on Linux and some other Unix systems.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] File access can be achieved through the native Java API, the Thrift API (generates a client in a number of languages e.g.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] C++, Java, Python, PHP, Ruby, Erlang, Perl, Haskell, C#, Cocoa, Smalltalk, and OCaml), the command-line interface, the HDFS-UI web application over HTTP, or via 3rd-party network client libraries.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] HDFS is designed for portability across various hardware platforms and for compatibility with a variety of underlying operating systems.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The HDFS design introduces portability limitations that result in some performance bottlenecks, since the Java implementation cannot use features that are exclusive to the platform on which HDFS is running.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Due to its widespread integration into enterprise-level infrastructure, monitoring HDFS performance at scale has become an increasingly important issue.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Monitoring end-to-end performance requires tracking metrics from datanodes, namenodes, and the underlying operating system.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] There are currently several monitoring platforms to track HDFS performance, including Hortonworks, Cloudera, and Datadog.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Hadoop works directly with any distributed file system that can be mounted by the underlying operating system by simply using a `file://` URL; however, this comes at a price – the loss of locality.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] To reduce network traffic, Hadoop needs to know which servers are closest to the data, information that Hadoop-specific file system bridges can provide.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] A number of third-party file system bridges have also been written, none of which are currently in Hadoop distributions.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] However, some commercial distributions of Hadoop ship with an alternative file system as the default – specifically IBM and MapR.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Atop the file systems comes the MapReduce Engine, which consists of one *JobTracker*, to which client applications submit MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The JobTracker pushes work to available *TaskTracker* nodes in the cluster, striving to keep the work as close to the data as possible.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] With a rack-aware file system, the JobTracker knows which node contains the data, and which other machines are nearby.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] If the work cannot be hosted on the actual node where the data resides, priority is given to nodes in the same rack.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] This reduces network traffic on the main backbone network.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] If a TaskTracker fails or times out, that part of the job is rescheduled.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The TaskTracker on each node spawns a separate Java virtual machine (JVM) process to prevent the TaskTracker itself from failing if the running job crashes its JVM.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] A heartbeat is sent from the TaskTracker to the JobTracker every few minutes to check its status.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The Job Tracker and TaskTracker status and information is exposed by Jetty and can be viewed from a web browser.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] If one TaskTracker is very slow, it can delay the entire MapReduce job – especially towards the end, when everything can end up waiting for the slowest task.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] With speculative execution enabled, however, a single task can be executed on multiple slave nodes.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] By default Hadoop uses FIFO scheduling, and optionally 5 scheduling priorities to schedule jobs from a work queue.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] In version 0.19 the job scheduler was refactored out of the JobTracker, while adding the ability to use an alternate scheduler (such as the *Fair scheduler* or the *Capacity scheduler*, described next).
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler was developed by Facebook.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The goal of the fair scheduler is to provide fast response times for small jobs and quality of service (QoS) for production jobs.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The fair scheduler has three basic concepts.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Each pool is assigned a guaranteed minimum share.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] By default, jobs that are uncategorized go into a default pool.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Pools have to specify the minimum number of map slots, reduce slots, as well as a limit on the number of running jobs.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler was developed by Yahoo.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The capacity scheduler supports several features that are similar to those of the fair scheduler.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Free resources are allocated to queues beyond their total capacity.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Within a queue, a job with a high level of priority has access to the queue's resources.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] There is no preemption once a job is running.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The biggest difference between Hadoop 1 and Hadoop 2 is the addition of YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator), which replaced the MapReduce engine in the first version of Hadoop.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] YARN strives to allocate resources to various applications effectively.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] It runs two daemons, which take care of two different tasks: the *resource manager*, which does job tracking and resource allocation to applications, the *application master*, which monitors progress of the execution.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] There are important features provided by Hadoop 3.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] For example, while there is one single *namenode* in Hadoop 2, Hadoop 3, enables having multiple name nodes, which solves the single point of failure problem.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] In Hadoop 3, there are containers working in principle of Docker, which reduces time spent on application development.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] One of the biggest changes is that Hadoop 3 decreases storage overhead with erasure coding.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Also, Hadoop 3 permits usage of GPU hardware within the cluster, which is a very substantial benefit to execute deep learning algorithms on a Hadoop cluster.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The HDFS is not restricted to MapReduce jobs.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] It can be used for other applications, many of which are under development at Apache.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] The list includes the HBase database, the Apache Mahout machine learning system, and the Apache Hive data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Theoretically, Hadoop could be used for any workload that is batch-oriented rather than real-time, is very data-intensive, and benefits from parallel processing.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] It can also be used to complement a real-time system, such as lambda architecture, Apache Storm, Flink, and Spark Streaming.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Inc. launched what they claimed was the world's largest Hadoop production application.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Search Webmap is a Hadoop application that runs on a Linux cluster with more than 10,000 cores and produced data that was used in every Yahoo! web search query.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] There are multiple Hadoop clusters at Yahoo! and no HDFS file systems or MapReduce jobs are split across multiple data centers.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Every Hadoop cluster node bootstraps the Linux image, including the Hadoop distribution.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Work that the clusters perform is known to include the index calculations for the Yahoo! search engine.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] In June 2009, Yahoo! made the source code of its Hadoop version available to the open-source community.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] In 2010, Facebook claimed that they had the largest Hadoop cluster in the world with 21 PB of storage.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] In June 2012, they announced the data had grown to 100 PB and later that year they announced that the data was growing by roughly half a PB per day.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] As of 2013, Hadoop adoption had become widespread: more than half of the Fortune 50 companies used Hadoop.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] Influential papers on the birth, growth, and curation of Hadoop and big data processing include: Jeffrey Dean, Sanjay Ghemawat (2004) MapReduce: Simplified Data Processing on Large Clusters, Google.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] This paper inspired Doug Cutting to develop an open-source implementation of the Map-Reduce framework.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hadoop] He named it Hadoop, after his son's toy elephant.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Hive provides the necessary SQL abstraction to integrate SQL-like queries (HiveQL) into the underlying Java without the need to implement queries in the low-level Java API.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Hive facilitates the integration of SQL-based querying languages with Hadoop, which is commonly used in data warehousing applications.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] While initially developed by Facebook, Apache Hive is used and developed by other companies such as Netflix and the Financial Industry Regulatory Authority (FINRA).
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Amazon maintains a software fork of Apache Hive included in Amazon Elastic MapReduce on Amazon Web Services.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Apache Hive supports the analysis of large datasets stored in Hadoop's HDFS and compatible file systems such as Amazon S3 filesystem and Alluxio.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] It provides a SQL-like query language called HiveQL with schema on read and transparently converts queries to MapReduce, Apache Tez and Spark jobs.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] All three execution engines can run in Hadoop's resource negotiator, YARN (Yet Another Resource Negotiator).
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] By default, Hive stores metadata in an embedded Apache Derby database, and other client/server databases like MySQL can optionally be used.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The first four file formats supported in Hive were plain text, sequence file, optimized row columnar (ORC) format and RCFile.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Apache Parquet can be read via plugin in versions later than 0.10 and natively starting at 0.13.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Major components of the Hive architecture include the metastore, driver, compiler, optimizer, executor, and user interfaces.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The **metastore** stores metadata for each of the tables, such as their schema and location.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] It also includes partition metadata which helps the driver to track the progress of various data sets distributed over the cluster.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The data is stored in a traditional RDBMS format.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] This metadata enables the driver to keep track of the data.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] A backup server regularly replicates the data to provide recovery in case of data loss.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The **driver** acts like a controller which receives the HiveQL statements.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] It starts the execution of the statement by creating sessions and monitors the life cycle and progress of the execution.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] It stores the necessary metadata generated during the execution of a HiveQL statement.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The driver also acts as a collection point of data or query results obtained after the Reduce operation.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The **compiler** performs compilation of the HiveQL query, converting the query to an execution plan.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] This plan contains the tasks and steps needed to be performed by the Hadoop MapReduce to get the output as translated by the query.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The compiler converts the query to an abstract syntax tree (AST).
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] After checking for compatibility and compile time errors, it converts the AST to a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The DAG divides operators to MapReduce stages and tasks based on the input query and data.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The **optimizer** performs various transformations on the execution plan to produce an optimized DAG.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Transformations can be aggregated together, such as converting a pipeline of joins to a single join, for better performance.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] It can also split tasks, such as applying a transformation on data before a reduce operation, to provide better performance and scalability.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The logic of transformation used for optimization can be modified or pipelined using another optimizer.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] An optimizer called YSmart is a part of Apache Hive.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] This correlated optimizer merges correlated MapReduce jobs into a single MapReduce job, significantly reducing the execution time.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The **executor** executes the tasks after compilation and optimization.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] It interacts with the job tracker of Hadoop to schedule tasks to be run.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] It takes care of pipelining the tasks by making sure that a task with a dependency gets executed only if all other prerequisites have been completed.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] A command-line interface (CLI) provides a user interface for an external user to interact with Hive by submitting queries and instructions and monitoring the process status.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The **Thrift Server** allows external clients to interact with Hive over a network, similar to the JDBC or ODBC protocols.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] While based on SQL, HiveQL does not strictly follow the full SQL-92 standard.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] HiveQL offers extensions not in SQL, including *multi-table inserts,* and *creates tables as select*.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] HiveQL lacked support for transactions and materialized views, and offered only limited subquery support.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Support for insert, update, and delete with full ACID functionality was made available with release 0.14.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Internally, a compiler translates HiveQL statements into a directed acyclic graph of MapReduce, Tez, or Spark jobs, which are submitted to Hadoop for execution.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The word count program counts the number of times each word occurs in the input.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Checks if table docs exists and drops it if it does.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Creates a new table called docs with a single column of type STRING called line.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Loads the specified file or directory (In this case “input_file”) into the table.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] OVERWRITE specifies that the target table to which the data is being loaded into is to be re-written; Otherwise, the data would be appended.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The query `CREATE TABLE word_counts AS SELECT word, count(1) AS count` creates a table called word_counts with two columns: word and count.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] This query draws its input from the inner query `(SELECT explode(split(line, '\s')) AS word FROM docs) temp`, which splits the input words into different rows of a temporary table aliased as temp.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The `GROUP BY WORD` clause groups the results based on their keys, so that the count column holds the number of occurrences for each word of the word column.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The `ORDER BY WORDS` clause sorts the words alphabetically.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The storage and querying operations of Hive resemble those of traditional relational databases.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Although Hive utilizes an SQL-like dialect, differences exist in its structure and operation because it is built on top of the Hadoop ecosystem and operates within the design characteristics of Hadoop and MapReduce.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] A schema is applied to a table in traditional databases.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] In such traditional databases, the table typically enforces the schema when the data is loaded into the table.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] This enables the database to make sure that the data entered follows the representation of the table as specified by the table definition.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] This design is called *schema on write*.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] In comparison, Hive does not verify the data against the table schema on write.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Instead, it subsequently does run time checks when the data is read.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The two approaches have their own advantages and drawbacks.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Checking data against a table schema during load time adds operational overhead, meaning traditional databases require more time to load data.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Verification checks are performed during loading to detect corrupt data prior to query execution.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Because data validation occurs during or immediately after the load stage, subsequent query performance is optimized.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] In contrast, Hive loads data without initial schema verification, resulting in faster data loading but slower query execution times.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Hive can be utilized when the schema is unavailable during data ingestion and is instead defined dynamically at run time.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Transactions are key operations in traditional databases.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] As any typical RDBMS, Hive supports all four properties of transactions (ACID): Atomicity, Consistency, Isolation, and Durability.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Transactions in Hive were introduced in Hive 0.13 but were only limited to the partition level.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The recent version of Hive 0.14 had these functions fully added to support complete ACID properties.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Hive 0.14 and later provides different row level transactions such as *INSERT, DELETE and UPDATE*.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Enabling *INSERT, UPDATE, and DELETE* transactions require setting appropriate values for configuration properties such as `hive.support.concurrency`, `hive.enforce.bucketing`, and `hive.exec.dynamic.partition.mode`.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Hive v0.7.0 added integration with Hadoop security.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Hadoop began using Kerberos authorization support to provide security.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Kerberos allows for mutual authentication between client and server, where the client's request for a ticket is passed along with the request.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] In earlier versions of Hadoop, users could modify usernames via the `hadoop.job.ugi` property, and MapReduce operations ran under a shared default user identity (such as Hadoop or mapred).
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Following Hive v0.7.0's integration with Hadoop security, TaskTracker jobs are executed by the user who initiated them, and the username can no longer be spoofed by setting the `hadoop.job.ugi` property.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] Permissions for newly created files in Hive are dictated by the HDFS.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The Hadoop distributed file system authorization model uses three entities: user, group and others with three permissions: read, write and execute.
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The default permissions for newly created files can be set by changing the unmask value for the Hive configuration variable `hive.files.umask.value`..
[src:apache-hive/apache-hive] The default permissions for newly created files can be set by changing the unmask value for the Hive configuration variable `hive.files.umask.value`.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In computing, a **data warehouse** (**DW** or **DWH**), also known as an **enterprise data warehouse** (**EDW**), is a system used for reporting and data analysis and is a core component of business intelligence.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are central repositories of data integrated from disparate sources.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] They store current and historical data organized in a way that is optimized for data analysis, generation of reports, and developing insights across the integrated data.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] They are intended to be used by analysts and managers to help make organizational decisions.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The data stored in the warehouse is uploaded from operational systems (such as marketing or sales).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The data may pass through an operational data store and may require data cleansing for additional operations to ensure data quality before it is used in the data warehouse for reporting.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The two main workflows for building a data warehouse system are extract, transform, load (ETL) and extract, load, transform (ELT).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Operational databases are optimized for the preservation of data integrity and speed of recording of business transactions through use of database normalization and an entity–relationship model.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Operational system designers generally follow database normalization to ensure data integrity.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Fully normalized database designs often result in information from a business transaction being stored in dozens to hundreds of tables.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Relational databases are efficient at managing the relationships between these tables.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The databases have very fast insert/update performance because only a small amount of data in those tables is affected by each transaction.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] To improve performance, older data are periodically purged.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Data warehouses are optimized for analytic access patterns, which usually involve selecting specific fields rather than all fields as is common in operational databases.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Because of these differences in access, operational databases (loosely, OLTP) benefit from the use of a row-oriented database management system (DBMS), whereas analytics databases (loosely, OLAP) benefit from the use of a column-oriented DBMS.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Operational systems maintain a snapshot of the business, while warehouses maintain historic data through ETL processes that periodically migrate data from the operational systems to the warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Online analytical processing (OLAP) is characterized by a low rate of transactions and complex queries that involve aggregations.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Response time is an effective performance measure of OLAP systems.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] OLAP applications are widely used for data mining.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] OLAP databases store aggregated, historical data in multi-dimensional schemas (usually star schemas).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] OLAP systems typically have a data latency of a few hours, while data mart latency is closer to one day.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The OLAP approach is used to analyze multidimensional data from multiple sources and perspectives.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The three basic operations in OLAP are roll-up (consolidation), drill-down, and slicing & dicing.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Online transaction processing (OLTP) is characterized by a large numbers of short online transactions (INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] OLTP systems emphasize fast query processing and maintaining data integrity in multi-access environments.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] For OLTP systems, performance is the number of transactions per second.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] OLTP databases contain detailed and current data.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The schema used to store transactional databases is the entity model (usually 3NF).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Normalization is the norm for data modeling techniques in this system.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Predictive analytics is about finding and quantifying hidden patterns in the data using complex mathematical models to prepare for different future outcomes, including demand for products, and make better decisions.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] By contrast, OLAP focuses on historical data analysis and is reactive.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Predictive systems are also used for customer relationship management (CRM).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] A Database is an organized collection of data that is stored and managed electronically.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] It is designed to store, retrieve and manage structured data using a DBMS(Database Management Software) for querying and manipulating the data.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] A data mart is a simple data warehouse focused on a single subject or functional area.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Hence it draws data from a limited number of sources such as sales, finance or marketing.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Data marts are often built and controlled by a single department in an organization.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The sources could be internal operational systems, a central data warehouse, or external data.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Types of data marts include dependent, independent, and hybrid data marts.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] A Data lake is a centralized repository that stores large volume of data in raw format that is processed at the run time.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] It can collect data from multiple sources such as APIs, Files, databases, sensors, websites, etc.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Unlike data warehouses, data lakes stores data is structured, semi-structured and unstructured format that makes them usable for machine learning and big data processing.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The typical extract, transform, load (ETL)-based data warehouse uses staging, data integration, and access layers to house its key functions.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The staging layer or staging database stores raw data extracted from each of the disparate source data systems.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The integration layer integrates disparate data sets by transforming the data from the staging layer, often storing this transformed data in an operational data store (ODS) database.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The integrated data are then moved to yet another database, often called the data warehouse database, where the data is arranged into hierarchical groups, often called dimensions, and into facts and aggregate facts.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The combination of facts and dimensions is sometimes called a star schema.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The access layer helps users retrieve data.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The main source of the data is cleansed, transformed, catalogued, and made available for use by managers and other business professionals for data mining, online analytical processing, market research and decision support.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] However, the means to retrieve and analyze data, to extract, transform, and load data, and to manage the data dictionary are also considered essential components of a data warehousing system.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Many references to data warehousing use this broader context.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Thus, an expanded definition of data warehousing includes business intelligence tools, tools to extract, transform, and load data into the repository, and tools to manage and retrieve metadata.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] ELT-based data warehousing gets rid of a separate ETL tool for data transformation.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Instead, it maintains a staging area inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In this approach, data gets extracted from heterogeneous source systems and are then directly loaded into the data warehouse, before any transformation occurs.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] All necessary transformations are then handled inside the data warehouse itself.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Finally, the manipulated data gets loaded into target tables in the same data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] A data warehouse maintains a copy of information from the source transaction systems.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The concept of data warehousing dates back to the late 1980s when IBM researchers Barry Devlin and Paul Murphy developed the "business data warehouse".
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In essence, the data warehousing concept was intended to provide an architectural model for the flow of data from operational systems to decision support environments.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The concept attempted to address the various problems associated with this flow, mainly the high costs associated with it.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In the absence of a data warehousing architecture, an enormous amount of redundancy was required to support multiple decision support environments.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In larger corporations, it was typical for multiple decision support environments to operate independently.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Though each environment served different users, they often required much of the same stored data.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The process of gathering, cleaning and integrating data from various sources, usually from long-term existing operational systems (usually referred to as legacy systems), was typically in part replicated for each environment.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Moreover, the operational systems were frequently reexamined as new decision support requirements emerged.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Often new requirements necessitated gathering, cleaning and integrating new data from "data marts" that was tailored for ready access by users.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Additionally, with the publication of The IRM Imperative (Wiley & Sons, 1991) by James M.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Kerr, the idea of managing and putting a dollar value on an organization's data resources and then reporting that value as an asset on a balance sheet became popular.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In the book, Kerr described a way to populate subject-area databases from data derived from transaction-driven systems to create a storage area where summary data could be further leveraged to inform executive decision-making.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] This concept served to promote further thinking of how a data warehouse could be developed and managed in a practical way within any enterprise.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] A fact is a value or measurement in the system being managed.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Raw facts are ones reported by the reporting entity.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Raw facts are aggregated to higher levels in various dimensions to extract information more relevant to the service or business.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] These are called aggregated facts or summaries.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] For example, if there are three BTSs in a city, then the facts above can be aggregated to the city level in the network dimension.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The two most important approaches to store data in a warehouse are dimensional and normalized.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The dimensional approach uses a star schema as proposed by Ralph Kimball.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The normalized approach, also called the third normal form (3NF) is an entity-relational normalized model proposed by Bill Inmon.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In a dimensional approach, transaction data is partitioned into "facts", which are usually numeric transaction data, and "dimensions", which are the reference information that gives context to the facts.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] This dimensional approach makes data easier to understand and speeds up data retrieval.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Dimensional structures are easy for business users to understand because the structure is divided into measurements/facts and context/dimensions.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Facts are related to the organization's business processes and operational system, and dimensions are the context about them (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Another advantage is that the dimensional model does not involve a relational database every time.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Thus, this type of modeling technique is very useful for end-user queries in data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The model of facts and dimensions can also be understood as a data cube, where dimensions are the categorical coordinates in a multi-dimensional cube, the fact is a value corresponding to the coordinates.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] It is difficult to modify the warehouse structure if the organization changes the way it does business.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In the normalized approach, the data in the warehouse are stored following, to a degree, database normalization rules.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Normalized relational database tables are grouped into *subject areas* (for example, customers, products and finance).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] When used in large enterprises, the result is dozens of tables linked by a web of joins.(Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The main advantage of this approach is that it is straightforward to add information into the database.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Disadvantages include that, because of the large number of tables, it can be difficult for users to join data from different sources into meaningful information and access the information without a precise understanding of the date sources and the data structure of the data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Both normalized and dimensional models can be represented in entity–relationship diagrams because both contain joined relational tables.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The difference between them is the degree of normalization.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] These approaches are not mutually exclusive, and there are other approaches.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Dimensional approaches can involve normalizing data to a degree (Kimball, Ralph 2008).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In *Information-Driven Business*, Robert Hillard compares the two approaches based on the information needs of the business problem.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] He concludes that normalized models hold far more information than their dimensional equivalents (even when the same fields are used in both models) but at the cost of usability.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The technique measures information quantity in terms of information entropy and usability in terms of the Small Worlds data transformation measure.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In the *bottom-up* approach, data marts are first created to provide reporting and analytical capabilities for specific business processes.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] These data marts can then be integrated to create a comprehensive data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The data warehouse bus architecture is primarily an implementation of "the bus", a collection of confirmed dimensions and confirmed facts, which are dimensions that are shared (in a specific way) between facts in two or more data marts.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The *top-down* approach is designed using a normalized enterprise data model.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] "Atomic" data, that is, data at the greatest level of detail, are stored in the data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Dimensional data marts containing data needed for specific business processes or specific departments are created from the data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Data warehouses often use a spoke–hub distribution paradigm.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Legacy systems feeding the warehouse often include customer relationship management and enterprise resource planning, generating large amounts of data.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] To consolidate these various data models and facilitate the extract transform load process, data warehouses often make use of an operational data store, the information from which is parsed into the actual data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] To reduce data redundancy, larger systems often store the data in a normalized way.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Data marts for specific reports can then be built on top of the data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] A hybrid (also called ensemble) data warehouse database is kept on third normal form to eliminate data redundancy.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] A normal relational database, however, is not efficient for business intelligence reports where dimensional modelling is prevalent.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Small data marts can shop for data from the consolidated warehouse and use the filtered, specific data for the fact tables and dimensions required.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The data warehouse provides a single source of information from which the data marts can read, providing a wide range of business information.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The hybrid architecture allows a data warehouse to be replaced with a master data management repository where operational (not static) information could reside.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The data vault modeling components follow hub and spokes architecture.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] This modeling style is a hybrid design, consisting of the best practices from both third normal form and star schema.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The data vault model is not a true third normal form, and breaks some of its rules, but it is a top-down architecture with a bottom up design.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The data vault model is geared to be strictly a data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] It is not geared to be end-user accessible, which, when built, still requires the use of a data mart or star schema-based release area for business purposes.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] There are basic features that define the data in the data warehouse that include subject orientation, data integration, time-variant, nonvolatile data, and data granularity.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Unlike the operational systems, the data in the data warehouse revolves around the subjects of the enterprise.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Subject orientation is not database normalization.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Subject orientation can be really useful for decision-making.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Gathering the required objects is called subject-oriented.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The data found within the data warehouse is integrated.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Since it comes from several operational systems, all inconsistencies must be removed.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Consistencies include naming conventions, measurement of variables, encoding structures, physical attributes of data, and so forth.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] While operational systems reflect current values as they support day-to-day operations, data warehouse data represents a long time horizon (up to 10 years) which means it stores mostly historical data.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] It is mainly meant for data mining and forecasting.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The data in the data warehouse is read-only, which means it cannot be updated, created, or deleted (unless there is a regulatory or statutory obligation to do so).
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In the data warehouse process, data can be aggregated in data marts at different levels of abstraction.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The user may start looking at the total sale units of a product in an entire region.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Then the user looks at the states in that region.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Finally, they may examine the individual stores in a certain state.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Therefore, typically, the analysis starts at a higher level and drills down to lower levels of details.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources creating a virtual data warehouse.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The different methods used to construct/organize a data warehouse specified by an organization are numerous.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] The hardware utilized, software created and data resources specifically required for the correct functionality of a data warehouse are the main components of the data warehouse architecture.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] All data warehouses have multiple phases in which the requirements of the organization are modified and fine-tuned.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Data warehouses in this stage of evolution are updated on a regular time cycle (usually daily, weekly or monthly) from the operational systems and the data is stored in an integrated reporting-oriented database.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] Data warehouses at this stage are updated from data in the operational systems on a regular basis and the data warehouse data are stored in a data structure designed to facilitate reporting.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] These data warehouses assemble data from different areas of business, so users can look up the information they need across other systems.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] In the healthcare sector, data warehouses are critical components of health informatics, enabling the integration, storage, and analysis of large volumes of clinical, administrative, and operational data.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] These systems consolidate information from disparate sources such as electronic health records (EHRs), laboratory information systems, picture archiving and communication systems (PACS), and medical billing platforms.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] By centralizing data, healthcare data warehouses support a range of functions including population health, clinical decision support, quality improvement, public health surveillance, and medical research.
[src:apache-hive/data-warehouse] These warehouses enable data-driven healthcare by supporting retrospective studies, comparative effectiveness research, and predictive analytics, often with the use of healthcare-applied artificial intelligence.
[src:apache-hive/query-language] A **query language**, also known as **data query language** or **database query language** (**DQL**), is a computer language used to make queries in databases and information systems.
[src:apache-hive/query-language] In database systems, query languages rely on strict theory to retrieve information.
[src:apache-hive/query-language] A well known example is the Structured Query Language (SQL).
[src:apache-hive/query-language] Broadly, query languages can be classified according to whether they are *database* query languages or *information retrieval* query languages.
[src:apache-hive/query-language] The difference is that a **database query language** attempts to give factual answers to factual questions, while an **information retrieval query language** attempts to find documents containing information that is relevant to an area of inquiry.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Introduced in the 1970s, SQL offered two main advantages over older read–write APIs such as ISAM or VSAM.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Firstly, it introduced the concept of accessing many records with one single command.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Secondly, it eliminates the need to specify *how* to reach a record, i.e., with or without an index.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Originally based upon relational algebra and tuple relational calculus, SQL consists of many types of statements, which may be informally classed as sublanguages, commonly: data query language (DQL), data definition language (DDL), data control language (DCL), and data manipulation language (DML).
[src:apache-hive/sql] The scope of SQL includes data query, data manipulation (insert, update, and delete), data definition (schema creation and modification), and data access control.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Although SQL is essentially a declarative language (4GL), it also includes procedural elements.
[src:apache-hive/sql] SQL was one of the first commercial languages to use Edgar F.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The model was described in his influential 1970 paper, "A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks".
[src:apache-hive/sql] Despite not entirely adhering to the relational model as described by Codd, SQL became the most widely used database language.
[src:apache-hive/sql] SQL became a standard of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) in 1986 and of the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) in 1987.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Since then, the standard has been revised multiple times to include a larger set of features and incorporate common extensions.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Despite the existence of standards, virtually no implementations in existence adhere to it fully, and most SQL code requires at least some changes before being ported to different database systems.
[src:apache-hive/sql] SQL was initially developed at IBM by Donald D.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Boyce after learning about the relational model from Edgar F.
[src:apache-hive/sql] This version, initially called SEQUEL (Structured English Query Language), was designed to manipulate and retrieve data stored in IBM's original quasirelational database management system, System R, which a group at IBM San Jose Research Laboratory had developed during the 1970s.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Chamberlin and Boyce's first attempt at a relational database language was SQUARE (Specifying Queries in A Relational Environment), but it was difficult to use due to subscript/superscript notation.
[src:apache-hive/sql] After moving to the San Jose Research Laboratory in 1973, they began work on a sequel to SQUARE.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The original name SEQUEL, which is widely regarded as a pun on QUEL, the query language of Ingres, was later changed to SQL (dropping the vowels) because "SEQUEL" was a trademark of the UK-based Hawker Siddeley Dynamics Engineering Limited company.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The label SQL later became the acronym for Structured Query Language.
[src:apache-hive/sql] After testing SQL at customer test sites to determine the usefulness and practicality of the system, IBM began developing commercial products based on their System R prototype, including System/38, SQL/DS, and IBM Db2, which were commercially available in 1979, 1981, and 1983, respectively.
[src:apache-hive/sql] IBM's endorsement caused the industry to move to SQL from alternatives like QUEL.
[src:apache-hive/sql] In the late 1970s, Relational Software, Inc.
[src:apache-hive/sql] (now Oracle Corporation) saw the potential of the concepts described by Codd, Chamberlin, and Boyce, and developed their own SQL-based RDBMS with aspirations of selling it to the U.S.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Navy, Central Intelligence Agency, and other U.S. government agencies.
[src:apache-hive/sql] In June 1979, Relational Software introduced one of the first commercially available implementations of SQL, Oracle V2 (Version2) for VAX computers.
[src:apache-hive/sql] By 1986, ANSI and ISO standard groups officially adopted the standard "Database Language SQL" language definition.
[src:apache-hive/sql] SQL implementations are incompatible between vendors and do not necessarily completely follow standards.
[src:apache-hive/sql] In particular, date and time syntax, string concatenation, `NULL`s, and comparison case sensitivity vary from vendor to vendor.
[src:apache-hive/sql] PostgreSQL and Mimer SQL strive for standards compliance, though PostgreSQL does not adhere to the standard in all cases.
[src:apache-hive/sql] For example, the folding of unquoted names to lower case in PostgreSQL is incompatible with the SQL standard, which says that unquoted names should be folded to upper case.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Thus, according to the standard, `Foo` should be equivalent to `FOO`, not `foo`.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Popular implementations of SQL commonly omit support for basic features of Standard SQL, such as the `DATE` or `TIME` data types.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The most obvious such examples, and incidentally the most popular commercial and proprietary SQL DBMSs, are Oracle (whose `DATE` behaves as `DATETIME`, and lacks a `TIME` type) and MS SQL Server (before the 2008 version).
[src:apache-hive/sql] As a result, SQL code can rarely be ported between database systems without modifications.
[src:apache-hive/sql] SQL was adopted as a standard by the ANSI in 1986 as SQL-86 and the ISO in 1987.
[src:apache-hive/sql] It is maintained by *ISO/IEC JTC 1, Information technology, Subcommittee SC 32, Data management and interchange*.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Until 1996, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) data-management standards program certified SQL DBMS compliance with the SQL standard.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Vendors now self-certify the compliance of their products.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The original standard declared that the official pronunciation for "SQL" was an initialism: /ˌɛsˌkjuːˈɛl/ ("ess cue el").
[src:apache-hive/sql] Regardless, many English-speaking database professionals (including Donald Chamberlin himself) use the acronym-like pronunciation of /ˈsiːkwəl/ ("sequel"), mirroring the language's prerelease development name, "SEQUEL".
[src:apache-hive/sql] The standard is commonly denoted by the pattern: *ISO/IEC 9075-n:yyyy Part n: title*, or, as a shortcut, *ISO/IEC 9075*.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Interested parties may purchase the standards documents from ISO, IEC, or ANSI.
[src:apache-hive/sql] SQL is designed for a specific purpose: to query data contained in a relational database.
[src:apache-hive/sql] SQL is a set-based, declarative programming language, not an imperative programming language like C or BASIC.
[src:apache-hive/sql] However, extensions to Standard SQL add procedural programming language functionality, such as control-of-flow constructs.
[src:apache-hive/sql] In addition to the standard SQL/PSM extensions and proprietary SQL extensions, procedural and object-oriented programmability is available on many SQL platforms via DBMS integration with other languages.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The SQL standard defines SQL/JRT extensions (SQL Routines and Types for the Java Programming Language) to support Java code in SQL databases.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Microsoft SQL Server 2005 uses the SQLCLR (SQL Server Common Language Runtime) to host managed .NET assemblies in the database, while prior versions of SQL Server were restricted to unmanaged extended stored procedures primarily written in C.
[src:apache-hive/sql] PostgreSQL lets users write functions in a wide variety of languages—including Perl, Python, Tcl, JavaScript (PL/V8) and C.
[src:apache-hive/sql] A distinction should be made between alternatives to SQL as a language, and alternatives to the relational model itself.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Below are proposed relational alternatives to the SQL language.
[src:apache-hive/sql] See navigational database and NoSQL for alternatives to the relational model.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Distributed Relational Database Architecture (DRDA) was designed by a workgroup within IBM from 1988 to 1994.
[src:apache-hive/sql] DRDA enables network-connected relational databases to cooperate to fulfill SQL requests.
[src:apache-hive/sql] An interactive user or program can issue SQL statements to a local RDB and receive tables of data and status indicators in reply from remote RDBs.
[src:apache-hive/sql] SQL statements can also be compiled and stored in remote RDBs as packages and then invoked by package name.
[src:apache-hive/sql] This is important for the efficient operation of application programs that issue complex, high-frequency queries.
[src:apache-hive/sql] It is especially important when the tables to be accessed are located in remote systems.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The messages, protocols, and structural components of DRDA are defined by the Distributed Data Management Architecture.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Distributed SQL processing ala DRDA is distinctive from contemporary distributed SQL databases.
[src:apache-hive/sql] SQL deviates in several ways from its theoretical foundation, the relational model and its tuple calculus.
[src:apache-hive/sql] In that model, a table is a set of tuples, while in SQL, tables and query results are lists of rows; the same row may occur multiple times, and the order of rows can be employed in queries (e.g., in the `LIMIT` clause).
[src:apache-hive/sql] Critics argue that SQL should be replaced with a language that returns strictly to the original foundation: for example, see *The Third Manifesto* by Hugh Darwen and C.J.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Early specifications did not support major features, such as primary keys.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Result sets could not be named, and subqueries had not been defined.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The lack of sum types has been described as a roadblock to full use of SQL's user-defined types.
[src:apache-hive/sql] JSON support, for example, needed to be added by a new standard in 2016.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The concept of Null is the subject of some debate.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The Null marker indicates the absence of a value, and is distinct from a value of 0 for an integer column or an empty string for a text column.
[src:apache-hive/sql] The concept of Nulls enforces the 3-valued-logic in SQL, which is a concrete implementation of the general 3-valued logic.
[src:apache-hive/sql] Another popular criticism is that it allows duplicate rows, making integration with languages such as Python, whose data types might make accurately representing the data difficult, in terms of parsing and by the absence of modularity.
[src:apache-hive/sql] This is usually avoided by declaring a primary key, or a unique constraint, with one or more columns that uniquely identify a row in the table.
[src:apache-hive/sql] In a sense similar to object–relational impedance mismatch, a mismatch occurs between the declarative SQL language and the procedural languages in which SQL is typically embedded.
